    <item>
      <title>Re: First 10 days in EQ</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Guides&amp;message.id=181#M181</link>
      <description>&lt;DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;1.&amp;nbsp; Learn tailoring and/or smithing:&amp;nbsp; Some of the newbie quest items take time and higher levels to acquire.&amp;nbsp; In the meantime, making some your own armour to compensate for the missing items, really helps.&amp;nbsp; It's more fashionable than wearing cloth and brings about a sense of accomplishment.&amp;nbsp; Since most newbies have small incomes, it best to save for and buy a good weapon in the bazaar and either quest or make your armour, until you have more funds available.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;2.&amp;nbsp; Learn baking:&amp;nbsp; For those who can't forage, baking is a cheap way of providing yourself with food.&amp;nbsp; Within a short time, you'll discover how easy it is to fill an entire bag with stacks of delicious, wholesome food.&amp;nbsp; There's nothing more satisfying than a homebaked meal to kill that gnawing in the pit of your stomach.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;3.&amp;nbsp; Practice, practice, practice:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;If you're a spellcaster, the best advice in the entire realm of Norath, is to practice your spells and keep up with what's required for your level -- which is 5 per level + 5.&amp;nbsp; Nothing is more embarassing and mana wasting,&amp;nbsp;than to try and cast a spell, only to&amp;nbsp;have it fizzle 30 times in row.&amp;nbsp; At that rate, by the time you got your spell off,&amp;nbsp;the other members of your group&amp;nbsp;would be dead and buried.&amp;nbsp; It's also very wise for those with special skills (such as: safe fall, tracking, kick, taunt, etc.)&amp;nbsp;to keep those maxed as well.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;4.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Learn to play your character:&amp;nbsp; While power-leveling up numerous levels at a time,&amp;nbsp;sounds wonderful and tempting, it can hamper you later on.&amp;nbsp; The most obvious reason is because your skills don't develop that rapidly and neither do your spell casting ability.&amp;nbsp; Sadly, there are&amp;nbsp;mid-level characters in the game,&amp;nbsp;who have low defense or offense, they can't cast their spells without fizzling numerous times, they're sub-standard with taunt, or can't hold agro.&amp;nbsp; So in the beginning,&amp;nbsp;have patience and take the time to learn your character and what others expect of them.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;5.&amp;nbsp; Fishing and Swimming:&amp;nbsp; Get that swimming skill up.&amp;nbsp; The higher the skill, the faster you swim.&amp;nbsp; There are many safe spots within various cities where you can build up that skill.&amp;nbsp; As for fishing, it's a convienient way to supply yourself with food and selling a stack of fresh fish can bring in a little extra cash.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;6.&amp;nbsp; Attitude and reputation:&amp;nbsp; Always keep in mind that each character earns a reputation, as does the person who's playing that character.&amp;nbsp; It pays to have a good one and you'll&amp;nbsp;discover people will enjoy having you in their group or will remember you kindly, years down the road.&amp;nbsp; Though we all make mistakes and is a painful part of the learning process, it's how you deal with the situation or the people involved that determines how you'll be viewed.&amp;nbsp; A bad reputation will spread faster than the wind and you'll find yourself alone.&amp;nbsp; No group will invite you and no guild will have you.&amp;nbsp; Consideration, thoughtfulness, respect, and kindness goes a long way.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;7.&amp;nbsp; GM's within the game:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;A time will come when you'll encounter a problem that can only be solved by a GM.&amp;nbsp; Sometimes they're hard to find and other times,&amp;nbsp;there will be more than one on.&amp;nbsp; The best way to deal with problems is to go to the Sony site&amp;nbsp;first and send an email to the&amp;nbsp;server GM.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;That way, if you don't have the time to wait online for a GM to get on, or your petition expires, they're still aware of your problem and will respond within a day or two via email.&amp;nbsp; Then within&amp;nbsp;the game, if a GM is on, petition.&amp;nbsp; Be patient --&amp;nbsp;if the GM doesn't get back to&amp;nbsp;you immediately, then he/she is probably busy dealing with someone else.&amp;nbsp; When the GM does respond to you, state your problem&amp;nbsp;quickly and clearly.&amp;nbsp; Answer any questions he/she may ask.&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;It's&amp;nbsp;extremely helpful&amp;nbsp;to be nice and courteous, even though you may be upset because you're missing a valuable piece of armour or stuck under the world.&amp;nbsp; Your attitude goes a long way with a GM,&amp;nbsp;who has been dealing with nothing but problems for hours on end.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;8.&amp;nbsp; Passing on the good deed:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Frequently&amp;nbsp;the higher level characters will decide to&amp;nbsp;pass on&amp;nbsp;an item they can no longer use, to a newbie -- or they'll decide to hand out some of the items they've made with their tradeskills.&amp;nbsp; It could be a piece of armour, a weapon, a robe, a piece of jewelry with stats, or a bag full of goodies.&amp;nbsp; If you happen to be one of the lucky people who received such a gift, keep in&amp;nbsp;mind that someday you'll have an item that's not worth selling in the bazaar, but would make a decent hand-me-down to a newbie.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;So pass on the good-will and&amp;nbsp;find a deserving newbie.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The thrill of receiving or giving such a gift, is worth a thousand words -- and&amp;nbsp;an action&amp;nbsp;the newbie won't ever forget.&lt;/DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;</description>
      <pubDate>Sun, 31 Oct 2004 12:30:29 GMT</pubDate>
      <author>Aaleline</author>
      <guid>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Guides&amp;message.id=181#M181</guid>
      <dc:creator>Aaleline</dc:creator>
